  <main class="page-main">
    <h1 class="page-title">Metallicity Gradients</h1>

    <p><strong>Metallicity gradients</strong> describe how chemical abundances (e.g., [Fe/H], [X/H]) vary with galactocentric radius in galaxies. They are key observables constraining star formation history, gas flows, and radial migration processes in disk and bulge components.</p>

    <h2 id="section-0">Definitions</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Radial metallicity gradient:</strong> slope of abundance vs. galactocentric radius (dex kpc<sup>-1</sup>).</li>
      <li><strong>Population-dependent gradients:</strong> different stellar populations (age, kinematics, chemistry) can show distinct gradients.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2 id="section-1">Observational Results</h2>
    <p>In the Milky Way, the thin disk generally shows a negative radial metallicity gradient, while the thick disk may show flatter or inverted trends depending on sample selection<sup>[1]</sup>.</p>
    <p>Recent APOGEE-based work finds that bulge-bar populations show population-dependent gradients: Sales-Silva et al. (2026) report slightly negative gradients for low-[Mg/Fe] low-eccentricity stars, slightly positive gradients for high-[Mg/Fe] low-eccentricity stars, and approximately flat gradients for high-eccentricity populations within R &lt; 6 kpc<sup>[2]</sup>.</p>

    <h2 id="section-2">Physical Interpretation</h2>
    <p>Gradient sign and slope encode radial variations in star formation timescales, gas accretion/expulsion, and stellar migration. Positive inner gradients can indicate centrally concentrated older populations or age gradients along bar/peanut structures as suggested by Sales-Silva et al. (2026)<sup>[2]</sup>.</p>

